; Boot the whole kernel with a root filesystem attached, into USER MODE, and run /etc/init.
;
; Every other test in this directory links a handful of kernel objects against a forged
; environment and drives one component.  This one links nothing: it loads the real `unix'
; image (built one directory up by kernel/CMakeLists.txt) with the same root3072.disk that
; fstest reads, and lets main() run the actual boot -- startup(), intrinit(), binit(),
; iinit(), iget() of the root, newproc() -- and then lets process 1 leave the kernel and
; exec the program the image carries.
;
; WHAT THE BANNER PROVES.  `console init' is the first thing /etc/init writes
; (kernel/test/coninit.S), and for it to appear at all, everything below had to work:
;   * main() returned, so iinit() did not panic -- bread(rootdev, SUPERB) completed without
;     B_ERROR (else panic "iinit"), sbcheck() accepted the superblock (else panic "no root
;     fs"), and iget(rootdev, ROOTINO) read the root inode.  That is task 20's "done when",
;     and this test is still the regression guard for the b_un.b_addr fat-pointer fix (before
;     it, sbcheck() mis-read s_bsize and panicked, stopping in panic()'s own `stop' loop);
;   * _start's second half forged a user context and left through `выпр', so РП really maps
;     the image copyout() wrote and the machine really entered user mode;
;   * the icode executed out of that copy, so copyout() put the words where РП says they are;
;   * `$77 SYS_exec' vectored to 0577, the gate framed the machine, syscall() marshalled the
;     arguments and exec() ran namei() over a user-space `char *' -- and this time namei()
;     FOUND the file, getxfile() read the BESM-6 a.out and setregs() started it (task 21);
;   * and coninit's own `$77 SYS_open' and `$77 SYS_write' reached cdevsw[0], so scopen()
;     ran, ttyopen() took the terminal and ttwrite() put characters on the wire -- task 23's
;     opening move.
;
; THIS TEST USED TO ASSERT THE OPPOSITE.  With no /etc/init on the image the exec came back
; with ENOENT and the icode fell into its `spin' loop, which is what the assertions checked.
; Task 23 put an init there, so `spin' is now the FAILURE case; the breakpoint below is kept
; purely to diagnose it, since ACC and r14 there say exactly why exec() refused the file.
;
; WHAT THIS TEST DOES NOT DO IS TALK TO INIT.  It watches for the banner and stops.  The
; typed line, the erase and kill characters, ^D and /dev/tty belong to console.ini next door.
; Keeping them apart keeps the diagnosis apart too: a failure here says "the kernel never got
; a user program running", a failure there says "the line discipline is wrong".
;
; `step', not `go': a hang must fail the run instead of hanging it -- `go' has no step bound.
;
; `set mmu cache' is needed since task 22: the boot programs РП (estabur -> sureg) and writes
; user memory through the map (copyout), so the БРЗ write-back is worth modelling here.
;
; WHAT THIS TEST DOES NOT CHECK: main()'s drainbrz() after the copyout.  Deleting it leaves
; this test passing, because main()'s epilogue and _start's tail happen to issue enough kernel
; stores to evict the icode's lines by age before the выпр.  The drain is not decoration --
; breaking on the instruction after the copyout shows seven of the nine words still in
; BRZ0-BRZ7 with memory reading zero -- but that measurement is written up at the call site in
; main.c, and this test cannot see it.  Do not read a PASS here as a verdict on the drain.
;
; `attach -r', and emphatically NOT `-n' (the trap TODO.md warns about): -r because the image
; is a build artifact, and no -n because `attach -n' CREATES AND FORMATS an empty container,
; on which sbcheck() would fail and the boot would panic.
;
; THE DRUMS MUST BE ATTACHED TO EXEC ANYTHING.  They are swapdev (conf.c), and exece()
; stages the argument list there -- getblk/bawrite on the way in, bread on the way back --
; before it ever touches the new image.  With no drum that bread comes back B_ERROR and the
; exec fails with EIO, which is what this test found the first time it was run with an
; /etc/init to exec.  Here `-n' IS right: the drums are scratch and want to start empty.
; Their names are this test's own, since ctest runs the SIMH tests in parallel and console.ini
; needs a swap area of its own.
;
; THE CONSOLE IS ATTACHED NOW, and has to be -- the assertion is what init printed on it.
; `set tty25 raw' first, so the bytes go out untranslated (see the header of kernel/dev/sc.c)
; and `expect' sees the ASCII the kernel actually emitted.  Console output reaches the expect
; machinery through sim_putchar -> tmxr_putc_ln -> sim_exp_check, so no logging is needed.
;
; @SPIN@ is pulled from unix.nm by genboot.cmake at build time -- it is a LINKED address that
; moves as the kernel grows, which is why this file is generated rather than hardcoded.

reset
set cpu latin
set mmu cache
set tty25 raw

attach tty25 console
attach -r md00 root3072.disk
attach -n drum0 boot0.drum
attach -n drum1 boot1.drum
load ../unix

expect -c "console init" echof "PASS: boot -- the kernel mounted the root, entered user mode, exec'd /etc/init and it wrote on the console"; quit
break @SPIN@
step 50000000

; Only reached when the expect never fired.  BEWARE THE REGISTER NAMES: SIMH numbers index
; registers in OCTAL, so r14 is `M16' and r15 is `M17'.
if (PC == @SPIN@) echof "FAIL: exec of /etc/init failed, and the icode fell into its spin loop. r14 (SIMH M16) is the errno: 2 ENOENT means the image carries no /etc/init (is coninit staged? see root.manifest), 8 ENOEXEC means getxfile() rejected the a.out header, 13 EACCES means the mode is not executable. ACC and r14:"; ex ACC; ex M16; exit 1
echof "FAIL: the boot never printed init's banner. A PC in panic()'s stop loop means iinit() panicked (no root fs / iinit) -- e.g. the b_un.b_addr fat-pointer fix was reverted; a PC in the kernel means process 1 never left it, and if the step count ran out it hung, in idle() if something slept and never woke. Look the PC up in unix.nm. PC:"
ex PC
exit 1
